            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> * I don't see a compelling reason to change the argument order for the `make_*_params` functions. That's causing churn. For what? We can instead make the `offset_encoding` required. But that should first cause a warning instead.\r\n\r\nIts advantage is that when called by default, especially for `make_given_range_params`, there is no need to use `vim.lsp.util.make_given_range_params(nil, nil, nil, \"utf-8\")`, because having the required parameters at the end makes the convenience of optional parameters meaningless (they cannot be empty, explicitly passing `nil` is needed at least). Additionally, adjusting parameters can facilitate the next step (if needed) to merge `make_given_range_params` and `make_range_params`, allowing `start_pos` and `end_pos` to come later. **But I am very open to this**, as many plugins are using it, and the impact will be significant.\r\n\r\nHowever, it is worth noting that compared to simply making `offset_encoding` required, the adjustment in order brings *additional* change requirements for the downstream, is only when they fulfilled the parameters already, like this:\r\n```lua\r\nvim.lsp.util.make_range_params(0, \"utf-8\")\r\n```\r\nThey need to change it to:\r\n```lua\r\nvim.lsp.util.make_range_params(\"utf-8\", 0)\r\n```\r\nBecause apart from this, as long as one parameter is empty, regardless of whether the parameter order is adjusted, the downstream must make corresponding changes, because `position_encoding` is the last parameter. And the situation above is also just a warning instead of breaking functionalities.",
